“Hi.” “I’m doing fine.” “I’m having a wonderful time.” “I’ll be home on Sunday.” These are the things I tell my parents when they ask how I am. I tell them I’m fine when I am not. I tell them I’m having a wonderful time when I’m miserable. I tell them I’ll be home on Sunday when I’m not. I tell them I’m okay when I’m not okay. I tell them I’m happy when I’m not. I tell them I’m fine when I’m not. When my parents ask me how I am, I lie. I tell them I’m fine when I’m not because I don’t want them to worry. I tell them I’m having a wonderful time when I’m not because I don’t want them to be disappointed. I tell them I’ll be home on Sunday when I’m not because I don’t want them to be sad. I tell them I’m okay when I’m not because I don’t want them to think I’m a failure. I tell them I’m happy when I’m not because I don’t want them to worry about me. I tell them I’m fine when I’m not because I don’t want them to be disappointed in me. I tell them I’m fine when I’m not because I don’t want them to be sad. I tell them I’m fine when I’m not because I don’t want them to be angry at me. I tell them I’m fine when I
